{
  "texts": [
    "In some fossils, serial grinding and photographing (physical optical tomography) is the only method available to reveal their 3D morphology (Sutton et al. 2001).",
    "X-ray tomography, while the de facto volume imaging technique in paleontology, is often unsuitable for specimens where the attenuation properties of the fossil and its surrounding matrix are too similar for accurate data acquisition.",
    "Serial sectioning tomography presents multichannel, high dimensional datasets of samples which preclude the application of more conventional volume imaging techniques, and thus can be valuable for DL applications.",
    "However, data acquisition is often prohibitively time-consuming, with the large data quantities required for DL model training being challenging to acquire.",
    "Moreover, serial sectioning is prone to geometric inconsistencies, particularly in terms of the alignment of optical tomograms required to reconstruct accurate 3D models."
  ]
}